# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: mayer-s-relation
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] Thermodynamic temperature is typically expressed using the Kelvin scale, on which the unit of measurement is the *kelvin* (unit symbol: K).
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] This unit is the same interval as the degree Celsius, used on the Celsius scale but the scales are offset so that 0 K on the Kelvin scale corresponds to absolute zero.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] For comparison, a temperature of 295 K corresponds to 21.85 °C and 71.33 °F.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] Another absolute scale of temperature is the Rankine scale, which is based on the Fahrenheit degree interval.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] Thermodynamic temperature can be defined in purely thermodynamic terms using the Carnot cycle.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] Thermodynamic temperature was rigorously defined historically long before particles such as atoms, molecules, and electrons were fully understood.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] The International System of Units (SI) specifies the absolute scale for measuring temperature, and the unit of measure *kelvin* (symbol: K) for specific values along the scale.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] A temperature interval of one degree Celsius is the same as one kelvin.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] Since the 2019 revision of the SI, the kelvin has been defined in relation to the *physical property* underlying thermodynamic temperature: the kinetic energy of atomic free particle motion.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] The revision fixed the Boltzmann constant at exactly 1.380649×10−23 J⋅K−1.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] The property that imbues material substances with a temperature can be readily understood by examining the ideal gas law, which relates, through the Boltzmann constant, how heat energy causes precisely defined changes in the pressure and temperature of certain gases.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] This is because monatomic gases like helium and argon behave kinetically like freely moving perfectly elastic and spherical billiard balls that move only in a specific subset of the possible motions that can occur in matter: that comprising the three *translational* degrees of freedom.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] The translational degrees of freedom are the familiar billiard ball-like movements along the *x*-, *y*-, and *z*-axes of 3D space (see *Fig.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] This is why the noble gases all have the same heat capacity per atom and why that value is lowest of all the gases.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] Molecules (two or more chemically bound atoms), however, have *internal structure* and therefore have additional *internal* degrees of freedom (see *Fig.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] 3*, below), which has the effect that molecules absorb more heat energy for any given rise in temperature than do the monatomic gases.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] Heat energy is born in all available degrees of freedom; this is in accordance with the equipartition theorem, so all available internal degrees of freedom have the same average energy as do their three external degrees of freedom.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] However, the property that gives all gases their pressure, which is the net force per unit area on a container arising from gas particles recoiling off it, is a function of the kinetic energy borne in the freely moving atoms' and molecules' three translational degrees of freedom.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] Fixing the Boltzmann constant at a specific value had the effect of precisely establishing the magnitude of the kelvin in terms of the average kinetic behavior of the noble gases.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] Moreover, the *starting point* of the thermodynamic temperature scale, absolute zero, was reaffirmed as the point at which *zero average kinetic energy* remains in a sample; the only remaining particle motion being that comprising random vibrations due to zero-point energy.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] The numerical zero of a temperature scale is not bound to the absolute zero of temperature.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] Nevertheless, some temperature scales have their numerical zero coincident with the absolute zero of temperature.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] Examples are the Kelvin temperature scale and the Rankine temperature scale.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] Other temperature scales have their numerical zero far from the absolute zero of temperature.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] Examples are the Celsius scale and the Fahrenheit scale.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] At the zero point of thermodynamic temperature, absolute zero, the particle constituents of matter have minimal motion and can become no colder.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] Absolute zero, which is a temperature of zero kelvins (0 K), precisely corresponds to −273.15 °C and −459.67 °F.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] Matter at absolute zero has no remaining transferable average kinetic energy and the only remaining particle motion is due to an ever-pervasive quantum mechanical phenomenon called ZPE (zero-point energy).
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] Temperature is generally expressed in absolute terms when scientifically examining temperature's interrelationships with certain other physical properties of matter such as its volume or pressure (see Gay-Lussac's law), or the wavelength of its emitted black-body radiation.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] Absolute temperature is also useful when calculating chemical reaction rates (see Arrhenius equation).
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] Though there have been many other temperature scales throughout history, there have been only two scales for measuring thermodynamic temperature which have absolute zero as their null point (0): The Kelvin scale and the Rankine scale.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] Throughout the scientific world where modern measurements are nearly always made using the International System of Units, thermodynamic temperature is measured using the Kelvin scale.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] The Rankine scale is part of English engineering units and finds use in certain engineering fields, particularly in legacy reference works.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] The Rankine scale uses the *degree Rankine* (symbol: °R) as its unit, which is the same magnitude as the degree Fahrenheit (symbol: °F).
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] A unit increment of one kelvin is exactly 1.8 times one degree Rankine; thus, to convert a specific temperature on the Kelvin scale to the Rankine scale, ***x* K = 1.8 *x* °R**, and to convert from a temperature on the Rankine scale to the Kelvin scale, ***x* °R = *x*/1.8 K**.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] Consequently, absolute zero is "0" for both scales, but the melting point of water ice (0 °C and 273.15 K) is 491.67 °R.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] To convert temperature *intervals* (a span or difference between two temperatures), the formulas from the preceding paragraph are applicable; for instance, an interval of 5 kelvins is precisely equal to an interval of 9 degrees Rankine.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] For 65 years, between 1954 and the 2019 revision of the SI, a temperature interval of one kelvin was defined as ⁠1/273.16⁠ of the temperature difference between the triple point of water and absolute zero.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] The net effect of this as well as later resolutions was twofold: 1) they defined absolute zero as precisely 0 K, and 2) they defined that the triple point of special isotopically controlled water called Vienna Standard Mean Ocean Water occurred at precisely 273.16 K and 0.01 °C.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] One effect of the aforementioned resolutions was that the melting point of water, while *very* close to 273.15 K and 0 °C, was not a defining value and was subject to refinement with more precise measurements.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] This shortcoming was addressed by the International Temperature Scale of 1990, or ITS‑90, which defined 13 additional points, from 13.8033 K, to 1,357.77 K.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] While definitional, ITS‑90 had—and still has—some challenges, partly because eight of its extrapolated values depend upon the melting or freezing points of metal samples, which must remain exceedingly pure lest their melting or freezing points be affected—usually depressed.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] The solution required that four physical constants, including the Boltzmann constant, be definitionally fixed.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] Assigning the Boltzmann constant a precisely defined value had no practical effect on modern thermometry except for the most exquisitely precise measurements.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] Afterwards, by defining the Boltzmann constant as exactly 1.380649×10−23 J/K, the 0.37 ppm uncertainty was transferred to the triple point of water, which became an experimentally determined value of 273.1600±0.0001 K (0.0100±0.0001 °C).
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] Notwithstanding the 2019 revision, water triple-point cells continue to serve in modern thermometry as exceedingly precise calibration references at 273.16 K and 0.01 °C.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] Moreover, the triple point of water remains one of the 14 calibration points comprising ITS‑90, which spans from the triple point of hydrogen (13.8033 K) to the freezing point of copper (1,357.77 K), which is a nearly hundredfold range of thermodynamic temperature.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] The thermodynamic temperature of any *bulk quantity* of a substance (a statistically significant quantity of particles) is directly proportional to the mean average kinetic energy of a specific kind of particle motion known as *translational motion*.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] These simple movements in the three *x*-, *y*-, and *z*-axes dimensions of space means the particles move in the three spatial *degrees of freedom*.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] This particular form of kinetic energy is sometimes referred to as *kinetic temperature*.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] Translational motion is but one form of heat energy and is what gives gases not only their temperature, but also their pressure and the vast majority of their volume.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] This relationship between the temperature, pressure, and volume of gases is established by the ideal gas law's formula *pV* = *nRT* and is embodied in the gas laws.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] Though the kinetic energy borne exclusively in the three translational degrees of freedom comprise the thermodynamic temperature of a substance, molecules, as can be seen in *Fig.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] 3*, can have other degrees of freedom, all of which fall under three categories: bond length, bond angle, and rotational.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] All three additional categories are not necessarily available to all molecules, and even for molecules that *can* experience all three, some can be "frozen out" below a certain temperature.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] The relationship of kinetic energy, mass, and velocity is given by the formula *E*k = ⁠1/2⁠*mv*2.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] Accordingly, particles with one unit of mass moving at one unit of velocity have precisely the same kinetic energy, and precisely the same temperature, as those with four times the mass but half the velocity.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] At any one instant, the proportion of particles moving at a given speed within this range is determined by probability as described by the Maxwell–Boltzmann distribution.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] 2* shows the speed distribution of 5500 K helium atoms.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] However, a certain proportion of atoms at any given instant are moving faster while others are moving relatively slowly; some are momentarily at a virtual standstill (off the *x*-axis to the right).
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] This graph uses *inverse speed* for its *x*-axis so the shape of the curve can easily be compared to the curves in *Fig.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] In both graphs, zero on the *x*-axis represents infinite temperature.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] Additionally, the *x*- and *y*-axes on both graphs are scaled proportionally.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] Although very specialized laboratory equipment is required to directly detect translational motions, the resultant collisions by atoms or molecules with small particles suspended in a fluid produces Brownian motion that can be seen with an ordinary microscope.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] The translational motions of elementary particles are *very* fast and temperatures close to absolute zero are required to directly observe them.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] For instance, when scientists at the NIST achieved a record-setting low temperature of 700 nK (billionths of a kelvin) in 1994, they used optical lattice laser equipment to adiabatically cool cesium atoms.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] They then turned off the entrapment lasers and directly measured atom velocities of 7 mm per second in order to calculate their temperature.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] Formulas for calculating the velocity and speed of translational motion are given in the following footnote.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] It is neither difficult to imagine atomic motions due to kinetic temperature, nor distinguish between such motions and those due to zero-point energy.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] Consider the following hypothetical thought experiment, as illustrated in *Fig.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] 2.5* at left, with an atom that is exceedingly close to absolute zero.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] Imagine peering through a common optical microscope set to 400 power, which is about the maximum practical magnification for optical microscopes.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] Such microscopes generally provide fields of view a bit over 0.4 mm in diameter.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] At the center of the field of view is a single levitated argon atom (argon comprises about 0.93% of air) that is illuminated and glowing against a dark backdrop.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] If this argon atom was at a beyond-record-setting *one-trillionth* of a kelvin above absolute zero, and was moving perpendicular to the field of view towards the right, it would require 13.9 seconds to move from the center of the image to the 200 μm tick mark.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] As the argon atom slowly moved, the positional jitter due to zero-point energy would be much less than the 200 nm (0.0002 mm) resolution of an optical microscope.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] Importantly, the atom's translational velocity of 14.43 μm/s constitutes all its retained kinetic energy due to not being precisely at absolute zero.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] Were the atom *precisely* at absolute zero, imperceptible jostling due to zero-point energy would cause it to very slightly wander, but the atom would perpetually be located, on average, at the same spot within the field of view.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] This is analogous to a boat that has had its motor turned off and is now bobbing slightly in relatively calm and windless ocean waters; even though the boat randomly drifts to and fro, it stays in the same spot in the long term and makes no headway through the water.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] Accordingly, an atom that was precisely at absolute zero would not be "motionless", and yet, a statistically significant collection of such atoms would have zero net kinetic energy available to transfer to any other collection of atoms.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] This is because regardless of the kinetic temperature of the second collection of atoms, they too experience the effects of zero-point energy.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] Such are the consequences of statistical mechanics and the nature of thermodynamics.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] As mentioned above, there are other ways molecules can jiggle besides the three translational degrees of freedom that imbue substances with their kinetic temperature.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] As can be seen in the animation at right, molecules are complex objects; they are a population of atoms and thermal agitation can strain their internal chemical bonds in three different ways: via rotation, bond length, and bond angle movements; these are all types of *internal degrees of freedom*.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] This makes molecules distinct from *monatomic* substances (consisting of individual atoms) like the noble gases helium and argon, which have only the three translational degrees of freedom (the *x*-, *y*-, and *z*-axes).
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] Kinetic energy is stored in molecules' internal degrees of freedom, which gives them an *internal temperature*.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] Even though these motions are called "internal", the external portions of molecules still move—rather like the jiggling of a stationary water balloon.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] This permits the two-way exchange of kinetic energy between internal motions and translational motions with each molecular collision.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] Accordingly, as internal energy is removed from molecules, both their kinetic temperature (the kinetic energy of translational motion) and their internal temperature simultaneously diminish in equal proportions.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] This phenomenon is described by the equipartition theorem, which states that for any bulk quantity of a substance in equilibrium, the kinetic energy of particle motion is evenly distributed among all the active degrees of freedom available to the particles.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] The kinetic energy stored internally in molecules causes substances to contain more heat energy at any given temperature and to absorb additional internal energy for a given temperature increase.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] This is because any kinetic energy that is, at a given instant, bound in internal motions, is not contributing to the molecules' translational motions at that same instant.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] This extra kinetic energy simply increases the amount of internal energy that substance absorbs for a given temperature rise.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] This property is known as a substance's specific heat capacity.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] Different molecules absorb different amounts of internal energy for each incremental increase in temperature; that is, they have different specific heat capacities.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] High specific heat capacity arises, in part, because certain substances' molecules possess more internal degrees of freedom than others do.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] For instance, room-temperature nitrogen, which is a diatomic molecule, has *five* active degrees of freedom: the three comprising translational motion plus two rotational degrees of freedom internally.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] Not surprisingly, in accordance with the equipartition theorem, nitrogen has five-thirds the specific heat capacity per mole (a specific number of molecules) as do the monatomic gases.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] Another example is gasoline (see table showing its specific heat capacity).
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] Gasoline can absorb a large amount of heat energy per mole with only a modest temperature change because each molecule comprises an average of 21 atoms and therefore has many internal degrees of freedom.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] Even larger, more complex molecules can have dozens of internal degrees of freedom.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] One particular heat conduction mechanism occurs when translational motion, the particle motion underlying temperature, transfers momentum from particle to particle in collisions.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] In gases, these translational motions are of the nature shown above in *Fig.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] As can be seen in that animation, not only does momentum (heat) diffuse throughout the volume of the gas through serial collisions, but entire molecules or atoms can move forward into new territory, bringing their kinetic energy with them.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] Consequently, temperature differences equalize throughout gases very quickly—especially for light atoms or molecules; convection speeds this process even more.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] Translational motion in *solids*, however, takes the form of *phonons* (see *Fig.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] Phonons are constrained, quantized wave packets that travel at the speed of sound of a given substance.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] The manner in which phonons interact within a solid determines a variety of its properties, including its thermal conductivity.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] In electrically insulating solids, phonon-based heat conduction is *usually* inefficient and such solids are considered *thermal insulators* (such as glass, plastic, rubber, ceramic, and rock).
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] This is because in solids, atoms and molecules are locked into place relative to their neighbors and are not free to roam.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] Metals however, are not restricted to only phonon-based heat conduction.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] Thermal energy conducts through metals extraordinarily quickly because instead of direct molecule-to-molecule collisions, the vast majority of thermal energy is mediated via very light, mobile *conduction electrons*.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] This is why there is a near-perfect correlation between metals' thermal conductivity and their electrical conductivity.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] Conduction electrons imbue metals with their extraordinary conductivity because they are *delocalized* (i.e., not tied to a specific atom) and behave rather like a sort of quantum gas due to the effects of *zero-point energy* (for more on ZPE, see *Note 1* below).
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] Furthermore, electrons are relatively light with a rest mass only 1⁄1836 that of a proton.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] However, a bullet accelerates faster than a rifle given an equal force.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] Since kinetic energy increases as the square of velocity, nearly all the kinetic energy goes into the bullet, not the rifle, even though both experience the same force from the expanding propellant gases.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] In the same manner, because they are much less massive, thermal energy is readily borne by mobile conduction electrons.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] Additionally, because they are delocalized and *very* fast, kinetic thermal energy conducts extremely quickly through metals with abundant conduction electrons.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] Thermal radiation is a byproduct of the collisions arising from various vibrational motions of atoms.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] These collisions cause the electrons of the atoms to emit thermal photons (known as black-body radiation).
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] Photons are emitted anytime an electric charge is accelerated (as happens when electron clouds of two atoms collide).
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] Even *individual molecules* with internal temperatures greater than absolute zero also emit black-body radiation from their atoms.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] In any bulk quantity of a substance at equilibrium, black-body photons are emitted across a range of wavelengths in a spectrum that has a bell curve-like shape called a Planck curve (see graph in *Fig.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] The top of a Planck curve (the peak emittance wavelength) is located in a particular part of the electromagnetic spectrum depending on the temperature of the black-body.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] Substances at extreme cryogenic temperatures emit at long radio wavelengths whereas extremely hot temperatures produce short gamma rays (see § Table of thermodynamic temperatures).
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] Black-body radiation diffuses thermal energy throughout a substance as the photons are absorbed by neighboring atoms, transferring momentum in the process.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] Black-body photons also easily escape from a substance and can be absorbed by the ambient environment; kinetic energy is lost in the process.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] As established by the Stefan–Boltzmann law, the intensity of black-body radiation increases as the fourth power of absolute temperature.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] Thus, a black-body at 824 K (just short of glowing dull red) emits 60 times the radiant power as it does at 296 K (room temperature).
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] This is why one can so easily feel the radiant heat from hot objects at a distance.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] At higher temperatures, such as those found in an incandescent lamp, black-body radiation can be the principal mechanism by which thermal energy escapes a system.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] The table below shows various points on the thermodynamic scale, in order of increasing temperature.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] For a true black body (which the plasma was not).
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] The Z machine's dominant emission originated from 40 MK electrons (soft x–ray emissions) within the plasma.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] The kinetic energy of particle motion is just one contributor to the total thermal energy in a substance; another is *phase transitions*, which are the potential energy of molecular bonds that can form in a substance as it cools (such as during condensing and freezing).
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] The thermal energy required for a phase transition is called *latent heat*.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] This phenomenon may more easily be grasped by considering it in the reverse direction: latent heat is the energy required to *break* chemical bonds (such as during evaporation and melting).
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] Almost everyone is familiar with the effects of phase transitions; for instance, steam at 100 °C can cause severe burns much faster than the 100 °C air from a hair dryer.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] This occurs because a large amount of latent heat is liberated as steam condenses into liquid water on the skin.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] Even though thermal energy is liberated or absorbed during phase transitions, pure chemical elements, compounds, and eutectic alloys exhibit no temperature change whatsoever while they undergo them (see *Fig.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] Consider one particular type of phase transition: melting.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] When a solid is melting, crystal lattice chemical bonds are being broken apart; the substance is transitioning from what is known as a *more ordered state* to a *less ordered state*.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] 7*, the melting of ice is shown within the lower left box heading from blue to green.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] At one specific thermodynamic point, the melting point (which is 0 °C across a wide pressure range in the case of water), all the atoms or molecules are, on average, at the maximum energy threshold their chemical bonds can withstand without breaking away from the lattice.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] Chemical bonds are all-or-nothing forces: they either hold fast, or break; there is no in-between state.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] The effect is rather like popcorn: at a certain temperature, additional thermal energy cannot make the kernels any hotter until the transition (popping) is complete.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] If the process is reversed (as in the freezing of a liquid), thermal energy must be removed from a substance.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] As stated above, the thermal energy required for a phase transition is called *latent heat*.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] In the specific cases of melting and freezing, it is called *enthalpy of fusion* or *heat of fusion*.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] If the molecular bonds in a crystal lattice are strong, the heat of fusion can be relatively great, typically in the range of 6 to 30 kJ per mole for water and most of the metallic elements.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] If the substance is one of the monatomic gases (which have little tendency to form molecular bonds) the heat of fusion is more modest, ranging from 0.021 to 2.3 kJ per mole.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] Relatively speaking, phase transitions can be truly energetic events.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] To completely melt ice at 0 °C into water at 0 °C, one must add roughly 80 times the thermal energy as is required to increase the temperature of the same mass of liquid water by one degree Celsius.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] The metals' ratios are even greater, typically in the range of 400 to 1200 times.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] The phase transition of boiling is much more energetic than freezing.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] For instance, the energy required to completely boil or vaporize water (what is known as *enthalpy of vaporization*) is roughly 540 times that required for a one-degree increase.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] Water's sizable enthalpy of vaporization is why one's skin can be burned so quickly as steam condenses on it (heading from red to green in *Fig.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] 7* above); water vapors (gas phase) are liquefied on the skin with releasing a large amount of energy (enthalpy) to the environment including the skin, resulting in skin damage.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] Water's highly energetic enthalpy of vaporization is also an important factor underlying why *solar pool covers* (floating, insulated blankets that cover swimming pools when the pools are not in use) are so effective at reducing heating costs: they prevent evaporation.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] (In other words, taking energy from water when it is evaporated is limited.) For instance, the evaporation of just 20 mm of water from a 1.29 m-deep pool chills its water 8.4 °C (15.1 °F).
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] The total energy of all translational and internal particle motions, including that of conduction electrons, plus the potential energy of phase changes, plus zero-point energy of a substance comprise the *internal energy* of it.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] When particles of a substance are as close as possible to complete rest and retain only ZPE (zero-point energy)-induced quantum mechanical motion, the substance is at the temperature of absolute zero (T = 0).
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] Often, all the phase changes that *can* occur in a substance, *will* have occurred by the time it reaches absolute zero.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] Notably, T = 0 helium remains liquid at room pressure (*Fig.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] 9* at right) and must be under a pressure of at least 25 bar (2.5 MPa) to crystallize.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] This is because helium's heat of fusion (the energy required to melt helium ice) is so low (only 21 joules per mole) that the motion-inducing effect of zero-point energy is sufficient to prevent it from freezing at lower pressures.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] A further complication is that many solids change their crystal structure to more compact arrangements at extremely high pressures (up to millions of bars, or hundreds of gigapascals).
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] These are known as *solid–solid phase transitions* wherein latent heat is liberated as a crystal lattice changes to a more thermodynamically favorable, compact one.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] The above complexities make for rather cumbersome blanket statements regarding the internal energy in T = 0 substances.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] Regardless of pressure though, what *can* be said is that at absolute zero, all solids with a lowest-energy crystal lattice such those with a *closest-packed arrangement* (see *Fig.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] 8*, above left) contain minimal internal energy, retaining only that due to the ever-present background of zero-point energy.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] One can also say that for a given substance at constant pressure, absolute zero is the point of lowest *enthalpy* (a measure of work potential that takes internal energy, pressure, and volume into consideration).
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] Lastly, all T = 0 substances contain zero kinetic thermal energy.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] Thermodynamic temperature is useful not only for scientists, it can also be useful for lay-people in many disciplines involving gases.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] By expressing variables in absolute terms and applying Gay-Lussac's law of temperature/pressure proportionality, solutions to everyday problems are straightforward; for instance, calculating how a temperature change affects the pressure inside an automobile tire.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] If the tire has a cold gage pressure of 200 kPa, then its absolute pressure is 300 kPa.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] Room temperature ("cold" in tire terms) is 296 K.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] If the tire temperature is 20 °C hotter (20 kelvins), the solution is calculated as ⁠316 K/296 K⁠ = 6.8% greater thermodynamic temperature *and* absolute pressure; that is, an absolute pressure of 320 kPa, which is a gage pressure of 220 kPa.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] The thermodynamic temperature is closely linked to the ideal gas law and its consequences.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] It can be linked also to the second law of thermodynamics.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] The thermodynamic temperature can be shown to have special properties, and in particular can be seen to be uniquely defined (up to some constant multiplicative factor) by considering the efficiency of idealized heat engines.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] Thus the ratio *T*2/*T*1 of two temperatures *T*1 and *T*2 is the same in all absolute scales.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] Strictly speaking, the temperature of a system is well-defined only if it is at thermal equilibrium.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] From a microscopic viewpoint, a material is at thermal equilibrium if the quantity of heat between its individual particles cancel out.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] There are many possible scales of temperature, derived from a variety of observations of physical phenomena.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] Loosely stated, temperature differences dictate the direction of heat between two systems such that their combined energy is maximally distributed among their lowest possible states.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] To better understand the relationship between temperature and entropy, consider the relationship between heat, work and temperature illustrated in the Carnot heat engine.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] The engine converts heat into work by directing a temperature gradient between a higher temperature heat source, *T*H, and a lower temperature heat sink, *T*C, through a gas filled piston.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] The work done per cycle is equal in magnitude to net heat taken up, which is sum of the heat *q*H taken up by the engine from the high-temperature source, plus the waste heat given off by the engine, *q*C < 0.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] Thus the efficiency depends only on |*q*C| / |*q*H|.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] Carnot's theorem states that all reversible engines operating between the same heat reservoirs are equally efficient.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] In addition, a reversible heat engine operating between a pair of thermal reservoirs at temperatures *T*1 and *T*3 must have the same efficiency as one consisting of two cycles, one between *T*1 and another (intermediate) temperature *T*2, and the second between *T*2 and *T*3.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] Here, the engine 1 is the one cycle engine, and the engines 2 and 3 make the two cycle engine where there is the intermediate reservoir at *T*2.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] We also have used the fact that the heat $q_{2}$ passes through the intermediate thermal reservoir at $T_{2}$ without losing its energy.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] In order to have the consistency in the last equation, the heat $q_{2}$ flown from the engine 2 to the intermediate reservoir must be equal to the heat $q_{2}^{*}$ flown out from the reservoir to the engine 3.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] But since the first function is *not* a function of *T*2, the product of the final two functions *must* result in the removal of *T*2 as a variable.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] I.e. the ratio of heat exchanged is a function of the respective temperatures at which they occur.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] We can choose any monotonic function for our $g(T)$ ; it is a matter of convenience and convention that we choose $g(T)=T$ .
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] Choosing then *one* fixed reference temperature (i.e. triple point of water), we establish the thermodynamic temperature scale.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] Note that for *T*C = 0 the efficiency is 100% and that efficiency becomes greater than 100% for *T*C < 0, which is unrealistic.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p01] The function S is the entropy of the system, mentioned previously, and the change of S around any cycle is zero (as is necessary for any state function).
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p02] Guillaume Amontons (1663–1705) published two papers in 1702 and 1703 that may be used to credit him as being the first researcher to deduce the existence of a fundamental (thermodynamic) temperature scale featuring an absolute zero.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p02] He made the discovery while endeavoring to improve upon the air thermometers in use at the time.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p02] His J-tube thermometers comprised a mercury column that was supported by a fixed mass of air entrapped within the sensing portion of the thermometer.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p02] In thermodynamic terms, his thermometers relied upon the volume / temperature relationship of gas under constant pressure.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p02] His measurements of the boiling point of water and the melting point of ice showed that regardless of the mass of air trapped inside his thermometers or the weight of mercury the air was supporting, the reduction in air volume at the ice point was always the same ratio.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p02] This observation led him to posit that a sufficient reduction in temperature would reduce the air volume to zero.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p02] In fact, his calculations projected that absolute zero was equivalent to −240 °C—only 33.15 degrees short of the true value of −273.15 °C.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p02] Amonton's discovery of a one-to-one relationship between absolute temperature and absolute pressure was rediscovered a century later and popularized within the scientific community by Joseph Louis Gay-Lussac.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p02] Today, this principle of thermodynamics is commonly known as *Gay-Lussac's law* but is also known as *Amonton's law*.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p02] In 1742, Anders Celsius (1701–1744) created a "backwards" version of the modern Celsius temperature scale.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p02] In Celsius's original scale, zero represented the boiling point of water and 100 represented the melting point of ice.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p02] In his paper *Observations of two persistent degrees on a thermometer*, he recounted his experiments showing that ice's melting point was effectively unaffected by pressure.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p02] He also determined with remarkable precision how water's boiling point varied as a function of atmospheric pressure.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p02] He proposed that zero on his temperature scale (water's boiling point) would be calibrated at the mean barometric pressure at mean sea level.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p02] Coincident with the death of Anders Celsius in 1744, the botanist Carl Linnaeus (1707–1778) effectively reversed Celsius's scale upon receipt of his first thermometer featuring a scale where zero represented the melting point of ice and 100 represented water's boiling point.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p02] The custom-made *Linnaeus-thermometer*, for use in his greenhouses, was made by Daniel Ekström, Sweden's leading maker of scientific instruments at the time.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p02] For the next 204 years, the scientific and thermometry communities worldwide referred to this scale as the *centigrade scale*.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p02] Temperatures on the centigrade scale were often reported simply as *degrees* or, when greater specificity was desired, *degrees centigrade*.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p02] The symbol for temperature values on this scale was °C (in several formats over the years).
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p02] The 9th CGPM (General Conference on Weights and Measures and the CIPM (International Committee for Weights and Measures formally adopted *degree Celsius* (symbol: °C) in 1948.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p02] In his book *Pyrometrie* (1777) completed four months before his death, Johann Heinrich Lambert (1728–1777), sometimes incorrectly referred to as Joseph Lambert, proposed an absolute temperature scale based on the pressure/temperature relationship of a fixed volume of gas.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p02] This is distinct from the volume/temperature relationship of gas under constant pressure that Guillaume Amontons discovered 75 years earlier.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p02] Lambert stated that absolute zero was the point where a simple straight-line extrapolation reached zero gas pressure and was equal to −270 °C.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p02] Notwithstanding the work of Guillaume Amontons 85 years earlier, Jacques Alexandre César Charles (1746–1823) is often credited with discovering (circa 1787), but not publishing, that the volume of a gas under constant pressure is proportional to its absolute temperature.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p02] Joseph Louis Gay-Lussac (1778–1850) published work in 1802 (acknowledging the unpublished lab notes of Jacques Charles fifteen years earlier) describing how the volume of gas under constant pressure changes linearly with its absolute (thermodynamic) temperature.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p02] This behavior is called Charles's law and is one of the gas laws.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p02] His are the first known formulas to use the number 273 for the expansion coefficient of gas relative to the melting point of ice (indicating that absolute zero was equivalent to −273 °C).
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p02] William Thomson (1824–1907), also known as Lord Kelvin, wrote in his 1848 paper "On an Absolute Thermometric Scale" of the need for a scale whereby *infinite cold* (absolute zero) was the scale's zero point, and which used the degree Celsius for its unit increment.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p02] Like Gay-Lussac, Thomson calculated that absolute zero was equivalent to −273 °C on the air thermometers of the time.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p02] This absolute scale is known today as the Kelvin thermodynamic temperature scale.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p02] Thomson's value of −273 was derived from 0.00366, which was the accepted expansion coefficient of gas per degree Celsius relative to the ice point.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p02] The inverse of −0.00366 expressed to five significant digits is −273.22 °C which is remarkably close to the true value of −273.15 °C.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p02] In the paper he proposed to define temperature using idealized heat engines.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p02] Note that like Carnot, Kelvin worked under the assumption that heat is conserved ("the conversion of heat (or caloric) into mechanical effect is probably impossible"), and if heat Q goes into the heat engine, then heat Q must come out.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p02] Kelvin, realizing after Joule's experiments that heat is not a conserved quantity but is convertible with mechanical work, modified his scale in the 1851 work *An Account of Carnot's Theory of the Motive Power of Heat*.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p02] The above definition fixes the ratios between absolute temperatures, but it does not fix a scale for absolute temperature.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p02] For the scale, Thomson proposed to use the Celsius degree, that is, ${\frac {1}{100}}$ the interval between the freezing and the boiling point of water.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p02] In 1859 Macquorn Rankine (1820–1872) proposed a thermodynamic temperature scale similar to William Thomson's but which used the degree Fahrenheit for its unit increment, that is, ${\frac {1}{180}}$ the interval between the freezing and the boiling point of water.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p02] This absolute scale is known today as the Rankine thermodynamic temperature scale.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p02] Ludwig Boltzmann (1844–1906) made major contributions to thermodynamics between 1877 and 1884 through an understanding of the role that particle kinetics and black body radiation played.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p02] His name is now attached to several of the formulas used today in thermodynamics.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p02] Gas thermometry experiments carefully calibrated to the melting point of ice and boiling point of water showed in the 1930s that absolute zero was equivalent to −273.15 °C.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p02] Resolution 3 of the 9th General Conference on Weights and Measures (CGPM) in 1948 fixed the triple point of water at precisely 0.01 °C.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p02] At this time, the triple point still had no formal definition for its equivalent kelvin value, which the resolution declared "will be fixed at a later date".
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p02] The implication is that if the value of absolute zero measured in the 1930s was truly −273.15 °C, then the triple point of water (0.01 °C) was equivalent to 273.16 K.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p02] Additionally, both the International Committee for Weights and Measures (CIPM) and the CGPM formally adopted the name *Celsius* for the *degree Celsius* and the *Celsius temperature scale*.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p02] This, in combination with Resolution 3 of the 9th CGPM, had the effect of defining absolute zero as being precisely zero kelvins and −273.15 °C.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p02] Resolution 3 of the 13th CGPM in 1967/1968 renamed the unit increment of thermodynamic temperature *kelvin*, symbol K, replacing *degree absolute*, symbol °K.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p02] Further, feeling it useful to more explicitly define the magnitude of the unit increment, the 13th CGPM also decided in Resolution 4 that "The kelvin, unit of thermodynamic temperature, is the fraction 1/273.16 of the thermodynamic temperature of the triple point of water".
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p02] In November 2018, the 26th General Conference on Weights and Measures (CGPM) changed the definition of the Kelvin by fixing the Boltzmann constant to 1.380649×10−23 when expressed in the unit J/K.
[src:mayer-s-relation/absolute-temperature-p02] This change (and other changes in the definition of SI units) was made effective on the 144th anniversary of the Metre Convention, 20 May 2019.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] Temperature is a measure of the average kinetic energy of the molecules in a body.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] The faster the molecules are moving, the higher that body's temperature is.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] Specifically, it is a monotonic function of the average molecular kinetic energy of a substance.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] As the energy in the particles increases, they start moving faster and faster, weakening the intermolecular forces between them and therefore expanding the substance.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] When a substance is heated, molecules begin to vibrate and move more, usually creating more distance between them.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] The relative expansion (also called strain) divided by the change in temperature is called the material's *coefficient of linear thermal expansion.* For small temperature changes, this is nearly constant, but for larger changes it varies with temperature.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] The coefficient of thermal expansion typically increases with temperature, as higher thermal energy reduces intermolecular forces and allows greater atomic displacement.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] If an equation of state is available, it can be used to predict the values of the thermal expansion at all the required temperatures and pressures, along with many other state functions.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] A number of materials contract on heating within certain temperature ranges; this is usually called negative thermal expansion, rather than "thermal contraction".
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] Other materials are also known to exhibit negative thermal expansion.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] Fairly pure silicon has a negative coefficient of thermal expansion for temperatures between about 18 and 120 K (−255 and −153 °C; −427 and −244 °F).
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] ALLVAR Alloy 30, a titanium alloy, exhibits anisotropic negative thermal expansion across a wide range of temperatures.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] Unlike gases or liquids, solid materials tend to keep their shape when undergoing thermal expansion.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] Thermal expansion generally decreases with increasing bond energy, which also has an effect on the melting point of solids, so high melting point materials are more likely to have lower thermal expansion.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] In general, liquids expand slightly more than solids.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] The thermal expansion of glasses is slightly higher compared to that of crystals.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] At the glass transition temperature, rearrangements that occur in an amorphous material lead to characteristic discontinuities of the coefficient of thermal expansion and specific heat.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] These discontinuities allow detection of the glass transition temperature where a supercooled liquid transforms into a glass.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] Absorption or desorption of water (or other solvents) can change the size of many common materials; many organic materials change size much more due to this effect than due to thermal expansion.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] Common plastics exposed to water can, in the long term, expand by many percent.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] Thermal expansion changes the space between particles of a substance, which changes the volume of the substance while negligibly changing its mass (the negligible amount comes from mass–energy equivalence), thus changing its density, which has an effect on any buoyant forces acting on it.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] This plays a crucial role in the convection of unevenly heated fluid masses, notably making thermal expansion partly responsible for wind and ocean currents.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] The coefficient of thermal expansion describes how the size of an object changes with a change in temperature.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] Specifically, it measures the fractional change in size per degree change in temperature at a constant pressure, such that lower coefficients describe lower propensity for change in size.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] Several types of coefficients have been developed: volumetric, area, and linear.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] The choice of coefficient depends on the particular application and which dimensions are considered important.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] For solids, one might only be concerned with the change along a length, or over some area.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] The volumetric thermal expansion coefficient is the most basic thermal expansion coefficient, and the most relevant for fluids.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] In general, substances expand or contract when their temperature changes, with expansion or contraction occurring in all directions.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] Substances that expand at the same rate in every direction are called isotropic.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] For isotropic materials, the area and volumetric thermal expansion coefficient are, respectively, approximately twice and three times larger than the linear thermal expansion coefficient.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] The subscript "*p*" to the derivative indicates that the pressure is held constant during the expansion, and the subscript *V* stresses that it is the volumetric (not linear) expansion that enters this general definition.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] In the case of a gas, the fact that the pressure is held constant is important, because the volume of a gas will vary appreciably with pressure as well as temperature.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] For a gas of low density this can be seen from the ideal gas law.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] This section summarizes the coefficients for some common materials.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] For isotropic materials, the coefficients linear thermal expansion *α* and volumetric thermal expansion *αV* are related by *αV* = 3*α*.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] For liquids, usually the coefficient of volumetric expansion is listed and linear expansion is calculated here for comparison.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] For common materials, such as many metals and compounds, the thermal expansion coefficient is inversely proportional to the melting point.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] In the table below, the range for *α* is from 10−7 K−1 for hard solids to 10−3 K−1 for organic liquids.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] The highest linear coefficient in a solid has been reported for a Ti-Nb alloy.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] The formula *αV* ≈ 3*α* is usually used for solids.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] Volumetric coefficients shown which do not follow that rule are highlighted.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] When calculating thermal expansion it is necessary to consider whether the body is free to expand or is constrained.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] If the body is free to expand, the expansion or strain resulting from an increase in temperature can be simply calculated by using the applicable coefficient of thermal expansion.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] If the body is constrained so that it cannot expand, then internal stress will be caused (or changed) by a change in temperature.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] This stress can be calculated by considering the strain that would occur if the body were free to expand and the stress required to reduce that strain to zero, through the stress/strain relationship characterised by the elastic or Young's modulus.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] In the special case of solid materials, external ambient pressure does not usually appreciably affect the size of an object and so it is not usually necessary to consider the effect of pressure changes.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] Linear expansion means change in one dimension (length) as opposed to change in volume (volumetric expansion).
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] To a first approximation, the change in length measurements of an object due to thermal expansion is related to temperature change by a coefficient of linear thermal expansion (CLTE).
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] It is the fractional change in length per degree of temperature change.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] Assuming negligible effect of pressure, one may write: $\alpha _{L}={\frac {1}{L}}\,{\frac {\mathrm {d} L}{\mathrm {d} T}}$ where L is a particular length measurement and $\mathrm {d} L/\mathrm {d} T$ is the rate of change of that linear dimension per unit change in temperature.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] This estimation works well as long as the linear-expansion coefficient does not change much over the change in temperature $\Delta T$ , and the fractional change in length is small $\Delta L/L\ll 1$ .
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] If either of these conditions does not hold, the exact differential equation (using $\mathrm {d} L/\mathrm {d} T$ ) must be integrated.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] where $L_{\mathrm {initial} }$ is the length before the change of temperature and $L_{\mathrm {final} }$ is the length after the change of temperature.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] In the field of continuum mechanics, thermal expansion and its effects are treated as eigenstrain and eigenstress.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] The area thermal expansion coefficient relates the change in a material's area dimensions to a change in temperature.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] It is the fractional change in area per degree of temperature change.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] Ignoring pressure, one may write: $\alpha _{A}={\frac {1}{A}}\,{\frac {\mathrm {d} A}{\mathrm {d} T}}$ where A is some area of interest on the object, and $dA/dT$ is the rate of change of that area per unit change in temperature.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] This equation works well as long as the area expansion coefficient does not change much over the change in temperature $\Delta T$ , and the fractional change in area is small $\Delta A/A\ll 1$ .
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] If either of these conditions does not hold, the equation must be integrated.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] This means that the volume of a material changes by some fixed fractional amount.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] For example, a steel block with a volume of 1 cubic meter might expand to 1.002 cubic meters when the temperature is raised by 50 K.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] If a block of steel has a volume of 2 cubic meters, then under the same conditions, it would expand to 2.004 cubic meters, again an expansion of 0.2%.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] The volumetric expansion coefficient would be 0.2% for 50 K, or 0.004% K−1.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] If the expansion coefficient is known, the change in volume can be calculated ${\frac {\Delta V}{V}}=\alpha _{V}\Delta T$ where $\Delta V/V$ is the fractional change in volume (e.g., 0.002) and $\Delta T$ is the change in temperature (50 °C).
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] The above example assumes that the expansion coefficient did not change as the temperature changed and the increase in volume is small compared to the original volume.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] This is not always true, but for small changes in temperature, it is a good approximation.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] This ratio arises because volume is composed of three mutually orthogonal directions.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] Thus, in an isotropic material, for small differential changes, one-third of the volumetric expansion is in a single axis.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] As an example, take a cube of steel that has sides of length L.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] We can easily ignore the terms as Δ*L* is a small quantity which on squaring gets much smaller and on cubing gets smaller still.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] The above approximation holds for small temperature and dimensional changes (that is, when $\Delta T$ and $\Delta L$ are small), but it does not hold if trying to go back and forth between volumetric and linear coefficients using larger values of $\Delta T$ .
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] In this case, the third term (and sometimes even the fourth term) in the expression above must be taken into account.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] This ratio can be found in a way similar to that in the linear example above, noting that the area of a face on the cube is just $L^{2}$ .
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] Also, the same considerations must be made when dealing with large values of $\Delta T$ .
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] Put more simply, if the length of a cubic solid expands from 1.00 m to 1.01 m, then the area of one of its sides expands from 1.00 m2 to 1.02 m2 and its volume expands from 1.00 m3 to 1.03 m3.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] Materials with anisotropic structures, such as crystals (with less than cubic symmetry, for example martensitic phases) and many composites (with the homogenization of microstructure), will generally have different linear expansion coefficients $\alpha _{L}$ in different directions.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] As a result, the total volumetric expansion is distributed unequally among the three axes.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] If the crystal symmetry is monoclinic or triclinic, even the angles between these axes are subject to thermal changes.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] In such cases it is necessary to treat the coefficient of thermal expansion as a tensor with up to six independent elements.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] A good way to determine the elements of the tensor is to study the expansion by x-ray powder diffraction.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] The thermal expansion coefficient tensor for the materials possessing cubic symmetry (for e.g.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] Thermal expansion coefficients of solids usually show little dependence on temperature (except at very low temperatures) whereas liquids can expand at different rates at different temperatures.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] There are some exceptions: for example, cubic boron nitride exhibits significant variation of its thermal expansion coefficient over a broad range of temperatures.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] Another example is paraffin which in its solid form has a thermal expansion coefficient that is dependent on temperature.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] Since gases fill the entirety of the container which they occupy, the volumetric thermal expansion coefficient at constant pressure, $\alpha _{V}$ , is the only one of interest.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] For an ideal gas, a formula can be readily obtained by differentiation of the ideal gas law, $pV_{m}=RT$ .
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] This yields $p\mathrm {d} V_{m}+V_{m}\mathrm {d} p=R\mathrm {d} T$ where p is the pressure, $V_{m}$ is the molar volume ( $V_{m}=V/n$ , with n the total number of moles of gas), T is the absolute temperature and R is equal to the gas constant.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] This suggested that the volume of a gas cooled at about −273 °C would reach zero.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] In October 1848, William Thomson, a 24 year old professor of Natural Philosophy at the University of Glasgow, published the paper *On an Absolute Thermometric Scale*.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] In a footnote Thomson calculated that "infinite cold" (absolute zero) was equivalent to −273 °C (he called the temperature in °C as the "temperature of the air thermometers" of the time).
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] This value of "−273" was considered to be the temperature at which the ideal gas volume reaches zero.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] The thermal expansion of liquids is usually higher than in solids because the intermolecular forces present in liquids are relatively weak, and their constituent molecules are more mobile.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] Unlike solids, liquids have no definite shape and they take the shape of the container.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] Consequently, liquids have no definite length and area, so linear and areal expansions of liquids only have significance in that they may be applied to topics such as thermometry and estimates of sea level rising due to global climate change.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] Sometimes, *αL* is still calculated from the experimental value of *αV*.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] In general, liquids expand on heating, except cold water; below 4 °C it contracts, leading to a negative thermal expansion coefficient.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] At higher temperatures it shows more typical behavior, with a positive thermal expansion coefficient.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] The expansion of liquids is usually measured in a container.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] When a liquid expands in a vessel, the vessel expands along with the liquid.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] Hence the observed increase in volume (as measured by the liquid level) is not the actual increase in its volume.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] The expansion of the liquid relative to the container is called its *apparent expansion*, while the actual expansion of the liquid is called *real expansion* or *absolute expansion*.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] The ratio of apparent increase in volume of the liquid per unit rise of temperature to the original volume is called its *coefficient of apparent expansion*.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] The absolute expansion can be measured by a variety of techniques, including ultrasonic methods.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] Historically, this phenomenon complicated the experimental determination of thermal expansion coefficients of liquids, since a direct measurement of the change in height of a liquid column generated by thermal expansion is a measurement of the apparent expansion of the liquid.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] Thus the experiment simultaneously measures *two* coefficients of expansion and measurement of the expansion of a liquid must account for the expansion of the container as well.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] The initial drop in the height of the liquid column is not due to an initial contraction of the liquid, but rather to the expansion of the flask as it contacts the heat bath first.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] Soon after, the liquid in the flask is heated by the flask itself and begins to expand.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] Since liquids typically have a greater percent expansion than solids for the same temperature change, the expansion of the liquid in the flask eventually exceeds that of the flask, causing the level of liquid in the flask to rise.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] For small and equal rises in temperature, the increase in volume (real expansion) of a liquid is equal to the sum of the apparent increase in volume (apparent expansion) of the liquid and the increase in volume of the containing vessel.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] The absolute expansion of the liquid is the apparent expansion corrected for the expansion of the containing vessel.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] Induction shrink fitting is a common industrial method to pre-heat metal components between 150 °C and 300 °C thereby causing them to expand and allow for the insertion or removal of another component.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] There exist some alloys with a very small linear expansion coefficient, used in applications that demand very small changes in physical dimension over a range of temperatures.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] One of these is Invar 36, with expansion approximately equal to 0.6 × 10−6 K−1.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] These alloys are useful in aerospace applications where wide temperature swings may occur.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] Pullinger's apparatus is used to determine the linear expansion of a metallic rod in the laboratory.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] The apparatus consists of a metal cylinder closed at both ends (called a steam jacket).
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] It is provided with an inlet and outlet for the steam.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] The steam for heating the rod is supplied by a boiler which is connected by a rubber tube to the inlet.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] The center of the cylinder contains a hole to insert a thermometer.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] The rod under investigation is enclosed in a steam jacket.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] One of its ends is free, but the other end is pressed against a fixed screw.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] The position of the rod is determined by a micrometer screw gauge or spherometer.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] To determine the coefficient of linear thermal expansion of a metal, a pipe made of that metal is heated by passing steam through it.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] One end of the pipe is fixed securely and the other rests on a rotating shaft, the motion of which is indicated by a pointer.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] A suitable thermometer records the pipe's temperature.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] This enables calculation of the relative change in length per degree temperature change.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] The control of thermal expansion in brittle materials is a key concern for a wide range of reasons.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] For example, both glass and ceramics are brittle and uneven temperature causes uneven expansion which again causes thermal stress and this might lead to fracture.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] Ceramics need to be joined or work in concert with a wide range of materials and therefore their expansion must be matched to the application.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] Because glazes need to be firmly attached to the underlying porcelain (or other body type) their thermal expansion must be tuned to 'fit' the body so that crazing or shivering do not occur.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] Good example of products whose thermal expansion is the key to their success are CorningWare and the spark plug.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] The thermal expansion of ceramic bodies can be controlled by firing to create crystalline species that will influence the overall expansion of the material in the desired direction.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] In addition or instead the formulation of the body can employ materials delivering particles of the desired expansion to the matrix.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] The thermal expansion of glazes is controlled by their chemical composition and the firing schedule to which they were subjected.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] In most cases there are complex issues involved in controlling body and glaze expansion, so that adjusting for thermal expansion must be done with an eye to other properties that will be affected, and generally trade-offs are necessary.
[src:mayer-s-relation/coefficient-of-thermal-expansion] Heat-induced expansion has to be taken into account in most areas of engineering.
[src:mayer-s-relation/compressibility] The choice to define compressibility as the negative of the fraction makes compressibility positive in the (usual) case that an increase in pressure induces a reduction in volume.
[src:mayer-s-relation/compressibility] The reciprocal of compressibility at fixed temperature is called the isothermal bulk modulus.
[src:mayer-s-relation/compressibility] The specification above is incomplete, because for any object or system the magnitude of the compressibility depends strongly on whether the process is isentropic or isothermal.
[src:mayer-s-relation/compressibility] where the subscript T indicates that the partial differential is to be taken at constant temperature.
[src:mayer-s-relation/compressibility] For a solid, the distinction between the two is usually negligible.
[src:mayer-s-relation/compressibility] The ideal gas (where the particles do not interact with each other) is an abstraction.
[src:mayer-s-relation/compressibility] The particles in real materials interact with each other.
[src:mayer-s-relation/compressibility] Then, the relation between the pressure, density and temperature is known as the equation of state denoted by some function F .
[src:mayer-s-relation/compressibility] The Van der Waals equation is an example of an equation of state for a realistic gas.
[src:mayer-s-relation/compressibility] Knowing the equation of state, the compressibility can be determined for any substance.
[src:mayer-s-relation/compressibility] The inverse of the compressibility is called the bulk modulus, often denoted K (sometimes B or $\beta$ ).).
[src:mayer-s-relation/compressibility] The compressibility equation relates the isothermal compressibility (and indirectly the pressure) to the structure of the liquid.
[src:mayer-s-relation/compressibility] where γ is the heat capacity ratio, α is the volumetric coefficient of thermal expansion, *ρ* = *N*/*V* is the particle density, and $\Lambda =(\partial P/\partial T)_{V}$ is the thermal pressure coefficient.
[src:mayer-s-relation/compressibility] The term "compressibility" is also used in thermodynamics to describe deviations of the thermodynamic properties of a real gas from those expected from an ideal gas.
[src:mayer-s-relation/compressibility] where p is the pressure of the gas, T is its temperature, and $V_{m}$ is its molar volume, all measured independently of one another.
[src:mayer-s-relation/compressibility] Z can, in general, be either greater or less than unity for a real gas.
[src:mayer-s-relation/compressibility] The deviation from ideal gas behavior tends to become particularly significant (or, equivalently, the compressibility factor strays far from unity) near the critical point, or in the case of high pressure or low temperature.
[src:mayer-s-relation/compressibility] In these cases, a generalized compressibility chart or an alternative equation of state better suited to the problem must be utilized to produce accurate results.
[src:mayer-s-relation/compressibility] The Earth sciences use *compressibility* to quantify the ability of a soil or rock to reduce in volume under applied pressure.
[src:mayer-s-relation/compressibility] This concept is important for specific storage, when estimating groundwater reserves in confined aquifers.
[src:mayer-s-relation/compressibility] Geologic materials are made up of two portions: solids and voids (or same as porosity).
[src:mayer-s-relation/compressibility] The void space can be full of liquid or gas.
[src:mayer-s-relation/compressibility] Geologic materials reduce in volume only when the void spaces are reduced, which expel the liquid or gas from the voids.
[src:mayer-s-relation/compressibility] This can happen over a period of time, resulting in settlement.
[src:mayer-s-relation/compressibility] It is an important concept in geotechnical engineering in the design of certain structural foundations.
[src:mayer-s-relation/compressibility] For example, the construction of high-rise structures over underlying layers of highly compressible bay mud poses a considerable design constraint, and often leads to use of driven piles or other innovative techniques.
[src:mayer-s-relation/compressibility] The degree of compressibility of a fluid has strong implications for its dynamics.
[src:mayer-s-relation/compressibility] Most notably, the propagation of sound is dependent on the compressibility of the medium.
[src:mayer-s-relation/compressibility] Compressibility is an important factor in aerodynamics.
[src:mayer-s-relation/compressibility] At low speeds, the compressibility of air is not significant in relation to aircraft design, but as the airflow nears and exceeds the speed of sound, a host of new aerodynamic effects become important in the design of aircraft.
[src:mayer-s-relation/compressibility] These effects, often several of them at a time, made it very difficult for World War II era aircraft to reach speeds much beyond 800 km/h (500 mph).
[src:mayer-s-relation/compressibility] Many effects are often mentioned in conjunction with the term "compressibility", but regularly have little to do with the compressible nature of air.
[src:mayer-s-relation/compressibility] From a strictly aerodynamic point of view, the term should refer only to those side-effects arising as a result of the changes in airflow from an incompressible fluid (similar in effect to water) to a compressible fluid (acting as a gas) as the speed of sound is approached.
[src:mayer-s-relation/compressibility] There are two effects in particular, wave drag and critical mach.
[src:mayer-s-relation/compressibility] One complication occurs in hypersonic aerodynamics, where dissociation causes an increase in the "notional" molar volume because a mole of oxygen, as O2, becomes 2 moles of monatomic oxygen and N2 similarly dissociates to 2 N.
[src:mayer-s-relation/compressibility] Since this occurs dynamically as air flows over the aerospace object, it is convenient to alter the compressibility factor Z, defined for an initial 30 gram moles of air, rather than track the varying mean molecular weight, millisecond by millisecond.
[src:mayer-s-relation/compressibility] This pressure dependent transition occurs for atmospheric oxygen in the 2,500–4,000 K temperature range, and in the 5,000–10,000 K range for nitrogen.
[src:mayer-s-relation/compressibility] In transition regions, where this pressure dependent dissociation is incomplete, both beta (the volume/pressure differential ratio) and the differential, constant pressure heat capacity greatly increases.
[src:mayer-s-relation/compressibility] For moderate pressures, above 10,000 K the gas further dissociates into free electrons and ions.
[src:mayer-s-relation/compressibility] Z for the resulting plasma can similarly be computed for a mole of initial air, producing values between 2 and 4 for partially or singly ionized gas.
[src:mayer-s-relation/compressibility] Each dissociation absorbs a great deal of energy in a reversible process and this greatly reduces the thermodynamic temperature of hypersonic gas decelerated near the aerospace object.
[src:mayer-s-relation/compressibility] Ions or free radicals transported to the object surface by diffusion may release this extra (nonthermal) energy if the surface catalyzes the slower recombination process.
[src:mayer-s-relation/compressibility] For ordinary materials, the bulk compressibility (sum of the linear compressibilities on the three axes) is positive, that is, an increase in pressure squeezes the material to a smaller volume.
[src:mayer-s-relation/compressibility] This condition is required for mechanical stability.
[src:mayer-s-relation/compressibility] However, under very specific conditions, materials can exhibit a compressibility that can be negative.
[src:mayer-s-relation/gas-constant] The **molar gas constant** (also known as the **gas constant**, **universal gas constant**, or **ideal gas constant**) is denoted by the symbol *R* or *R*.
[src:mayer-s-relation/gas-constant] It is the molar equivalent to the Boltzmann constant, expressed in units of energy per temperature increment per amount of substance, rather than energy per temperature increment per *particle*.
[src:mayer-s-relation/gas-constant] The constant is also a combination of the constants from Boyle's law, Charles's law, Avogadro's law, and Gay-Lussac's law.
[src:mayer-s-relation/gas-constant] It is a physical constant that is featured in many fundamental equations in the physical sciences, such as the ideal gas law, the Arrhenius equation, and the Nernst equation.
[src:mayer-s-relation/gas-constant] The gas constant is the constant of proportionality that relates the energy scale in physics to the temperature scale and the scale used for amount of substance.
[src:mayer-s-relation/gas-constant] Thus, the value of the gas constant ultimately derives from historical decisions and accidents in the setting of units of energy, temperature and amount of substance.
[src:mayer-s-relation/gas-constant] The Boltzmann constant and the Avogadro constant were similarly determined, which separately relate energy to temperature and particle count to amount of substance.
[src:mayer-s-relation/gas-constant] Since the 2019 revision of the SI, both *N*A and *k* are defined with exact numerical values when expressed in SI units.
[src:mayer-s-relation/gas-constant] As a consequence, the SI value of the molar gas constant is exact.
[src:mayer-s-relation/gas-constant] Some have suggested that it might be appropriate to name the symbol *R* the **Regnault constant** in honour of the French chemist Henri Victor Regnault, whose accurate experimental data were used to calculate the early value of the constant.
[src:mayer-s-relation/gas-constant] However, the origin of the letter *R* to represent the constant is elusive.
[src:mayer-s-relation/gas-constant] The universal gas constant was apparently introduced independently by August Friedrich Horstmann (1873) and Dmitri Mendeleev who reported it first on 12 September 1874.
[src:mayer-s-relation/gas-constant] Using his extensive measurements of the properties of gases, Mendeleev also calculated it with high precision, within 0.3% of its modern value.
[src:mayer-s-relation/gas-constant] The gas constant occurs in the ideal gas law: $PV=nRT=mR_{\text{specific}}T,$ where *P* is the absolute pressure, *V* is the volume of gas, *n* is the amount of substance, *m* is the mass, and *T* is the thermodynamic temperature.
[src:mayer-s-relation/gas-constant] *R*specific is the mass-specific gas constant.
[src:mayer-s-relation/gas-constant] The gas constant is expressed in the same unit as molar heat.
[src:mayer-s-relation/gas-constant] From the ideal gas law $PV=nRT$ we get $R={\frac {PV}{nT}},$ where *P* is pressure, *V* is volume, *n* is the amount of a given substance, and *T* is temperature.
[src:mayer-s-relation/gas-constant] Area and volume are (length)2 and (length)3 respectively.
[src:mayer-s-relation/gas-constant] The physical significance of *R* is work per mole per kelvin.
[src:mayer-s-relation/gas-constant] Instead of a mole, the constant can be expressed by considering the normal cubic metre.
[src:mayer-s-relation/gas-constant] The Boltzmann constant *k*B (alternatively *k*) may be used in place of the molar gas constant by working in pure particle count, *N*, rather than amount of substance, *n*, since $R=N_{\text{A}}k_{\text{B}},$ where *N*A is the Avogadro constant.
[src:mayer-s-relation/gas-constant] For example, the ideal gas law in terms of the Boltzmann constant is $PV=Nk_{\text{B}}T,$ where *N* is the number of particles (molecules in this case), or to generalize to an inhomogeneous system the local form holds: $P=nk_{\text{B}}T,$ where *n* = *N*/*V* is the number density.
[src:mayer-s-relation/gas-constant] Finally, by defining the kinetic energy associated to the temperature, $T:=k_{\text{B}}T,$ the equation becomes simply $P=nT,$ which is the form usually encountered in statistical mechanics and other branches of theoretical physics.
[src:mayer-s-relation/gas-constant] As of 2006, the most precise measurement of *R* had been obtained by measuring the speed of sound *c*a(*P*, *T*) in argon at the temperature *T* of the triple point of water at different pressures *P*, and extrapolating to the zero-pressure limit *c*a(0, *T*).
[src:mayer-s-relation/gas-constant] However, following the 2019 revision of the SI, *R* now has an exact value defined in terms of other exactly defined physical constants.
[src:mayer-s-relation/gas-constant] Another important relationship comes from thermodynamics.
[src:mayer-s-relation/gas-constant] Mayer's relation relates the specific gas constant to the specific heat capacities for a calorically or thermally perfect gas: $R_{\text{specific}}=c_{P}-c_{V},$ where *cP* is the specific heat capacity for a constant pressure and *cV* is the specific heat capacity for a constant volume.
[src:mayer-s-relation/gas-constant] It is common, especially in engineering applications, to represent the specific gas constant by the symbol *R*.
[src:mayer-s-relation/gas-constant] In such cases, the universal gas constant is usually given a different symbol such as *R* to distinguish it.
[src:mayer-s-relation/gas-constant] In any case, the context and/or unit of the gas constant should make it clear as to whether the universal or specific gas constant is being referred to.
[src:mayer-s-relation/gas-constant] Then the molar mass of air is computed by *M*0 = *R*/*R*air = 28.964917 g/mol.
[src:mayer-s-relation/gas-constant] The use of the kilomole in the unit results in an extra factor of 1000 in the constant.
[src:mayer-s-relation/gas-constant] The USSA1976 acknowledges that their defined value of *R** is not consistent with the cited values for the Avogadro constant and the Boltzmann constant.
[src:mayer-s-relation/gas-constant] This disparity is not a significant departure from accuracy – *R*∗ is slightly greater than 99.998% of the actual value of the constant, *R* = 8.31446261815324 J⋅mol−1⋅K−1‍ – and USSA1976 uses this value of *R*∗ for all the calculations of the standard atmosphere.
[src:mayer-s-relation/gas-constant] When using the ISO value of *R*, the calculated pressure increases by only 0.62 pascal at 11 kilometres (the equivalent of a difference of only 17.4 centimetres or 6.8 inches) and 0.292 Pa at 20 km (the equivalent of a difference of only 33.8 cm or 13.2 in).
[src:mayer-s-relation/gas-constant] This definition was published well before the 2019 SI revision, through which the constant was given an exact value.
[src:mayer-s-relation/heat-capacity] The corresponding intensive property is the specific heat capacity, found by dividing the heat capacity of an object by its mass.
[src:mayer-s-relation/heat-capacity] Dividing the heat capacity by the amount of substance in moles yields its molar heat capacity.
[src:mayer-s-relation/heat-capacity] The volumetric heat capacity measures the heat capacity per volume.
[src:mayer-s-relation/heat-capacity] In architecture and civil engineering, the heat capacity of a building is often referred to as its *thermal mass*.
[src:mayer-s-relation/heat-capacity] The heat capacity of an object, denoted by C , is the limit $C=\lim _{\Delta T\to 0}{\frac {Q}{\Delta T}},$ where Q is the amount of heat that must be added to the object (of mass *M*) in order to raise its temperature by $\Delta T$ .
[src:mayer-s-relation/heat-capacity] The value of this parameter usually varies considerably depending on the starting temperature T of the object and the pressure p applied to it.
[src:mayer-s-relation/heat-capacity] In particular, it typically varies dramatically with phase transitions such as melting or vaporization (see enthalpy of fusion and enthalpy of vaporization).
[src:mayer-s-relation/heat-capacity] Therefore, it is considered a function $C(p,T)$ of those two variables.
[src:mayer-s-relation/heat-capacity] The variation can be ignored in contexts when working with objects in narrow ranges of temperature and pressure.
[src:mayer-s-relation/heat-capacity] For example, the heat capacity of a block of iron weighing one pound is about 204 J/K when measured from a starting temperature *T* = 25 °C and *P* = 1 atm of pressure.
[src:mayer-s-relation/heat-capacity] That approximate value is adequate for temperatures between 15 °C and 35 °C, and surrounding pressures from 0 to 10 atmospheres, because the exact value varies very little in those ranges.
[src:mayer-s-relation/heat-capacity] One can trust that the same heat input of 204 J will raise the temperature of the block from 15 °C to 16 °C, or from 34 °C to 35 °C, with negligible error.
[src:mayer-s-relation/heat-capacity] At constant pressure, heat supplied to the system contributes to both the work done and the change in internal energy, according to the first law of thermodynamics.
[src:mayer-s-relation/heat-capacity] where the final equality follows from the appropriate Maxwell relations, and is commonly used as the definition of the isobaric heat capacity.
[src:mayer-s-relation/heat-capacity] A system undergoing a process at constant volume implies that no expansion work is done, so the heat supplied contributes only to the change in internal energy.
[src:mayer-s-relation/heat-capacity] The heat capacity obtained this way is denoted $C_{V}.$ The value of $C_{V}$ is always less than the value of $C_{p}$ .
[src:mayer-s-relation/heat-capacity] where $N_{f}$ is the number of degrees of freedom of each individual particle in the gas, and $N_{i}=N_{f}-3$ is the number of internal degrees of freedom, where the number 3 comes from the three translational degrees of freedom (for a gas in 3D space).
[src:mayer-s-relation/heat-capacity] This means that a monoatomic ideal gas (with zero internal degrees of freedom) will have isochoric heat capacity $C_{v}={\frac {3nR}{2}}$ .
[src:mayer-s-relation/heat-capacity] Heat capacity of a system undergoing phase transition is infinite, because the heat is utilized in changing the state of the material rather than raising the overall temperature.
[src:mayer-s-relation/heat-capacity] Given an isochoric system, $C_{v}=\left({\frac {\partial U}{\partial T}}\right)_{N,V}$ , which can be rewritten as $\left.dU\right|_{N,V=const}=C_{v}dT$ .
[src:mayer-s-relation/heat-capacity] The heat capacity may be well-defined even for heterogeneous objects, with separate parts made of different materials; such as an electric motor, a crucible with some metal, or a whole building.
[src:mayer-s-relation/heat-capacity] In many cases, the (isobaric) heat capacity of such objects can be computed by simply adding together the (isobaric) heat capacities of the individual parts.
[src:mayer-s-relation/heat-capacity] However, this computation is valid only when all parts of the object are at the same external pressure before and after the measurement.
[src:mayer-s-relation/heat-capacity] For example, when heating an amount of gas in an elastic container, its volume *and pressure* will both increase, even if the atmospheric pressure outside the container is kept constant.
[src:mayer-s-relation/heat-capacity] Therefore, the effective heat capacity of the gas, in that situation, will have a value intermediate between its isobaric and isochoric capacities $C_{p}$ and $C_{V}$ .
[src:mayer-s-relation/heat-capacity] The heat energy that is supplied may end up as kinetic energy (energy of motion) and potential energy (energy stored in force fields), both at macroscopic and atomic scales.
[src:mayer-s-relation/heat-capacity] Then the change in temperature will depend on the particular path that the system followed through its phase space between the initial and final states.
[src:mayer-s-relation/heat-capacity] Namely, one must somehow specify how the positions, velocities, pressures, volumes, etc. changed between the initial and final states; and use the general tools of thermodynamics to predict the system's reaction to a small energy input.
[src:mayer-s-relation/heat-capacity] The "constant volume" and "constant pressure" heating modes are just two among infinitely many paths that a simple homogeneous system can follow.
[src:mayer-s-relation/heat-capacity] The heat capacity can usually be measured by the method implied by its definition: start with the object at a known uniform temperature, add a known amount of heat energy to it, wait for its temperature to become uniform, and measure the change in its temperature.
[src:mayer-s-relation/heat-capacity] This method can give moderately accurate values for many solids; however, it cannot provide very precise measurements, especially for gases.
[src:mayer-s-relation/heat-capacity] The SI unit for heat capacity of an object is joule per kelvin (J/K or J⋅K−1).
[src:mayer-s-relation/heat-capacity] Since an increment of temperature of one degree Celsius is the same as an increment of one kelvin, that is the same unit as J/°C.
[src:mayer-s-relation/heat-capacity] The heat capacity of an object is an amount of energy divided by a temperature change, which has the dimension L2⋅M⋅T−2⋅Θ−1.
[src:mayer-s-relation/heat-capacity] Therefore, the SI unit J/K is equivalent to kilogram meter squared per second squared per kelvin (kg⋅m2⋅s−2⋅K−1 ).
[src:mayer-s-relation/heat-capacity] In those contexts, the unit of heat capacity is 1 BTU/°R ≈ 1900 J/K.
[src:mayer-s-relation/heat-capacity] The BTU was in fact defined so that the average heat capacity of one pound of water would be 1 BTU/°F.
[src:mayer-s-relation/heat-capacity] In this regard, with respect to mass, note conversion of 1 Btu/lb⋅°R ≈ 4,187 J/kg⋅K and the calorie (below).
[src:mayer-s-relation/heat-capacity] In chemistry, heat amounts are often measured in calories.
[src:mayer-s-relation/heat-capacity] Most physical systems exhibit a positive heat capacity; constant-volume and constant-pressure heat capacities, rigorously defined as partial derivatives, are always positive for homogeneous bodies.
[src:mayer-s-relation/heat-capacity] However, even though it can seem paradoxical at first, there are some systems for which the heat capacity $Q/\Delta T$ is *negative*.
[src:mayer-s-relation/heat-capacity] Examples include a reversibly and nearly adiabatically expanding ideal gas, which cools, $\Delta T<0$ , while a small amount of heat $Q>0$ is put in, or combusting methane with increasing temperature, $\Delta T>0$ , and giving off heat, $Q<0$ .
[src:mayer-s-relation/heat-capacity] Others are inhomogeneous systems that do not meet the strict definition of thermodynamic equilibrium.
[src:mayer-s-relation/heat-capacity] They include gravitating objects such as stars and galaxies, and also some nano-scale clusters of a few tens of atoms close to a phase transition.
[src:mayer-s-relation/heat-capacity] A negative heat capacity can result in a negative temperature.
[src:mayer-s-relation/heat-capacity] If the system loses energy, for example, by radiating energy into space, the average kinetic energy actually increases.
[src:mayer-s-relation/heat-capacity] If a temperature is defined by the average kinetic energy, then the system therefore can be said to have a negative heat capacity.
[src:mayer-s-relation/heat-capacity] A more extreme version of this occurs with black holes.
[src:mayer-s-relation/heat-capacity] According to black-hole thermodynamics, the more mass and energy a black hole absorbs, the colder it becomes.
[src:mayer-s-relation/heat-capacity] In contrast, if it is a net emitter of energy, through Hawking radiation, it will become hotter and hotter until it boils away.
[src:mayer-s-relation/heat-capacity] According to the second law of thermodynamics, when two systems with different temperatures interact via a purely thermal connection, heat will flow from the hotter system to the cooler one (this can also be understood from a statistical point of view).
[src:mayer-s-relation/heat-capacity] Therefore, if such systems have equal temperatures, they are at thermal equilibrium.
[src:mayer-s-relation/heat-capacity] However, this equilibrium is stable only if the systems have *positive* heat capacities.
[src:mayer-s-relation/heat-capacity] For such systems, when heat flows from a higher-temperature system to a lower-temperature one, the temperature of the first decreases and that of the latter increases, so that both approach equilibrium.
[src:mayer-s-relation/heat-capacity] In contrast, for systems with *negative* heat capacities, the temperature of the hotter system will further increase as it loses heat, and that of the colder will further decrease, so that they will move farther from equilibrium.
[src:mayer-s-relation/heat-capacity] This means that the equilibrium is unstable.
[src:mayer-s-relation/heat-capacity] For example, according to theory, the smaller (less massive) a black hole is, the smaller its Schwarzschild radius will be, and therefore the greater the curvature of its event horizon will be, as well as its temperature.
[src:mayer-s-relation/heat-capacity] Thus, the smaller the black hole, the more thermal radiation it will emit and the more quickly it will evaporate by Hawking radiation.
[src:mayer-s-relation/ideal-gas] An **ideal gas** is a theoretical gas composed of many randomly moving point particles that are not subject to interparticle interactions.
[src:mayer-s-relation/ideal-gas] The ideal gas concept is useful because it obeys the ideal gas law, a simplified equation of state, and is amenable to analysis under statistical mechanics.
[src:mayer-s-relation/ideal-gas] The requirement of zero interaction can often be relaxed if, for example, the interaction is perfectly elastic or regarded as point-like collisions.
[src:mayer-s-relation/ideal-gas] Under various conditions of temperature and pressure, many real gases behave qualitatively like an ideal gas, where the gas molecules (or atoms for monatomic gas) play the role of the ideal particles.
[src:mayer-s-relation/ideal-gas] Noble gases, and mixtures such as air, have a considerable parameter range around standard temperature and pressure.
[src:mayer-s-relation/ideal-gas] One mole of an ideal gas has a volume of 22.71095464...
[src:mayer-s-relation/ideal-gas] L (exact value based on 2019 revision of the SI) at standard temperature and pressure (a temperature of 273.15 K and an absolute pressure of exactly 105 Pa).
[src:mayer-s-relation/ideal-gas] The ideal gas model tends to fail at lower temperatures or higher pressures, where intermolecular forces and molecular size become important.
[src:mayer-s-relation/ideal-gas] It also fails for most heavy gases, such as many refrigerants, and for gases with strong intermolecular forces, notably water vapor.
[src:mayer-s-relation/ideal-gas] At high pressures, the volume of a real gas is often considerably larger than that of an ideal gas.
[src:mayer-s-relation/ideal-gas] At low temperatures, the pressure of a real gas is often considerably less than that of an ideal gas.
[src:mayer-s-relation/ideal-gas] At some point of low temperature and high pressure, real gases undergo a phase transition, such as to a liquid or a solid.
[src:mayer-s-relation/ideal-gas] The model of an ideal gas, however, does not describe or allow phase transitions.
[src:mayer-s-relation/ideal-gas] These must be modeled by more complex equations of state.
[src:mayer-s-relation/ideal-gas] The deviation from the ideal gas behavior can be described by a dimensionless quantity, the compressibility factor, Z.
[src:mayer-s-relation/ideal-gas] The ideal gas model has been explored in both the Newtonian dynamics (as in "kinetic theory") and in quantum mechanics (as a "gas in a box").
[src:mayer-s-relation/ideal-gas] The ideal gas model has also been used to model the behavior of electrons in a metal (in the Drude model and the free electron model), and it is one of the most important models in statistical mechanics.
[src:mayer-s-relation/ideal-gas] If the pressure of an ideal gas is reduced in a throttling process the temperature of the gas does not change.
[src:mayer-s-relation/ideal-gas] The classical ideal gas can be separated into two types: The classical thermodynamic ideal gas and the ideal quantum Boltzmann gas.
[src:mayer-s-relation/ideal-gas] Both are essentially the same, except that the classical thermodynamic ideal gas is based on classical statistical mechanics, and certain thermodynamic parameters such as the entropy are only specified to within an undetermined additive constant.
[src:mayer-s-relation/ideal-gas] The ideal quantum Boltzmann gas overcomes this limitation by taking the limit of the quantum Bose gas and quantum Fermi gas in the limit of high temperature to specify these additive constants.
[src:mayer-s-relation/ideal-gas] The behavior of a quantum Boltzmann gas is the same as that of a classical ideal gas except for the specification of these constants.
[src:mayer-s-relation/ideal-gas] The results of the quantum Boltzmann gas are used in a number of cases including the Sackur–Tetrode equation for the entropy of an ideal gas and the Saha ionization equation for a weakly ionized plasma.
[src:mayer-s-relation/ideal-gas] The ideal gas law is an extension of experimentally discovered gas laws.
[src:mayer-s-relation/ideal-gas] It can also be derived from microscopic considerations.
[src:mayer-s-relation/ideal-gas] Real fluids at low density and high temperature approximate the behavior of a classical ideal gas.
[src:mayer-s-relation/ideal-gas] However, at lower temperatures or a higher density, a real fluid deviates strongly from the behavior of an ideal gas, particularly as it condenses from a gas into a liquid or as it deposits from a gas into a solid.
[src:mayer-s-relation/ideal-gas] This deviation is expressed as a compressibility factor.
[src:mayer-s-relation/ideal-gas] The other equation of state of an ideal gas must express Joule's second law, that the internal energy of a fixed mass of ideal gas is a function only of its temperature, with $U=U(n,T)$ .
[src:mayer-s-relation/ideal-gas] That U for an ideal gas depends only on temperature is a consequence of the ideal gas law (see Internal energy#Changes due to temperature and volume), although in the general case ĉV depends on temperature and an integral is needed to compute U.
[src:mayer-s-relation/ideal-gas] The probability distribution of particles by velocity or energy is given by the Maxwell speed distribution.
[src:mayer-s-relation/ideal-gas] The assumption of spherical particles is necessary so that there are no rotational modes allowed, unlike in a diatomic gas.
[src:mayer-s-relation/ideal-gas] The following three assumptions are very related: molecules are hard, collisions are elastic, and there are no inter-molecular forces.
[src:mayer-s-relation/ideal-gas] The assumption that the space between particles is much larger than the particles themselves is of paramount importance, and explains why the ideal gas approximation fails at high pressures.
[src:mayer-s-relation/ideal-gas] This quantity is generally a function of temperature due to intermolecular and intramolecular forces, but for moderate temperatures it is approximately constant.
[src:mayer-s-relation/ideal-gas] Specifically, the Equipartition Theorem predicts that the constant for a monatomic gas is *ĉV* = ⁠3/2⁠ while for a diatomic gas it is *ĉV* = ⁠5/2⁠ if vibrations are neglected (which is often an excellent approximation).
[src:mayer-s-relation/ideal-gas] Since the heat capacity depends on the atomic or molecular nature of the gas, macroscopic measurements on heat capacity provide useful information on the microscopic structure of the molecules.
[src:mayer-s-relation/ideal-gas] where *H* = *U* + *PV* is the enthalpy of the gas.
[src:mayer-s-relation/ideal-gas] The above is known as the **Mayer's relation**.
[src:mayer-s-relation/ideal-gas] Sometimes, a distinction is made between an ideal gas, where *ĉV* and *ĉP* could vary with temperature, and a perfect gas, for which this is not the case.
[src:mayer-s-relation/ideal-gas] For air, which is a mixture of gases that are mainly diatomic (nitrogen and oxygen), this ratio is often assumed to be 7/5, the value predicted by the classical Equipartition Theorem for diatomic gases.
[src:mayer-s-relation/ideal-gas] Using the results of thermodynamics only, we can go a long way in determining the expression for the entropy of an ideal gas.
[src:mayer-s-relation/ideal-gas] This is an important step since, according to the theory of thermodynamic potentials, if we can express the entropy as a function of U (U is a thermodynamic potential), volume V and the number of particles N, then we will have a complete statement of the thermodynamic behavior of the ideal gas.
[src:mayer-s-relation/ideal-gas] We will be able to derive both the ideal gas law and the expression for internal energy from it.
[src:mayer-s-relation/ideal-gas] where the reference variables may be functions of the number of particles N.
[src:mayer-s-relation/ideal-gas] where all constants have been incorporated into the logarithm as *f*(*N*) which is some function of the particle number N having the same dimensions as VTĉV in order that the argument of the logarithm be dimensionless.
[src:mayer-s-relation/ideal-gas] We now impose the constraint that the entropy is extensive, meaning that when the extensive parameters (V and N) are multiplied by a constant, the entropy is multiplied by the same constant.
[src:mayer-s-relation/ideal-gas] where Φ may vary for different gases but is independent of the thermodynamic state of the gas.
[src:mayer-s-relation/ideal-gas] Since this is an expression for entropy in terms of U, V, and N, it is a fundamental equation from which all other properties of the ideal gas may be derived.
[src:mayer-s-relation/ideal-gas] This is about as far as we can go using thermodynamics alone.
[src:mayer-s-relation/ideal-gas] Note that the above equation is flawed – as the temperature approaches zero, the entropy approaches negative infinity, in contradiction to the third law of thermodynamics.
[src:mayer-s-relation/ideal-gas] The above equation is a good approximation only when the argument of the logarithm is much larger than unity – the concept of an ideal gas breaks down at low values of ⁠V/N⁠.
[src:mayer-s-relation/ideal-gas] Nevertheless, there will be a "best" value of the constant in the sense that the predicted entropy is as close as possible to the actual entropy, given the flawed assumption of ideality.
[src:mayer-s-relation/ideal-gas] A quantum-mechanical derivation of this constant is developed in the derivation of the Sackur–Tetrode equation, which expresses the entropy of a monatomic (*ĉV* = 3/2) ideal gas.
[src:mayer-s-relation/ideal-gas] In the Sackur–Tetrode theory the constant depends only upon the mass of the gas particle.
[src:mayer-s-relation/ideal-gas] The Sackur–Tetrode equation also suffers from a divergent entropy at absolute zero but is a good approximation for the entropy of a monatomic ideal gas for high enough temperatures.
[src:mayer-s-relation/ideal-gas] For a mixture (*j*=1,2,...) of ideal gases, each at partial pressure *Pj*, it can be shown that the chemical potential *μj* will be given by the above expression with the pressure *P* replaced by *Pj*.
[src:mayer-s-relation/ideal-gas] The most informative way of writing the potentials is in terms of their natural variables, since each of these equations can be used to derive all of the other thermodynamic variables of the system.
[src:mayer-s-relation/ideal-gas] In statistical mechanics, the relationship between the Helmholtz free energy and the partition function is fundamental, and is used to calculate the thermodynamic properties of matter; see configuration integral for more details.
[src:mayer-s-relation/ideal-gas] In fact, quantum theory itself predicts the same thing.
[src:mayer-s-relation/ideal-gas] Any gas behaves as an ideal gas at high enough temperature and low enough density, but at the point where the Sackur–Tetrode equation begins to break down, the gas will begin to behave as a quantum gas, composed of either bosons or fermions.
[src:mayer-s-relation/ideal-gas] Gases tend to behave as an ideal gas over a wider range of pressures when the temperature reaches the Boyle temperature.
[src:mayer-s-relation/ideal-gas] where Λ is the thermal de Broglie wavelength of the gas and g is the degeneracy of states.
[src:mayer-s-relation/ideal-gas] The Sackur-Tetrode equation expresses the entropy of an ideal quantum Boltzmann gas for interparticle distances well above the thermal wavelength.
[src:mayer-s-relation/ideal-gas] An ideal gas of bosons (e.g. a photon gas) will be governed by Bose–Einstein statistics and the distribution of energy will be in the form of a Bose–Einstein distribution.
[src:mayer-s-relation/ideal-gas] An ideal gas of fermions will be governed by Fermi–Dirac statistics and the distribution of energy will be in the form of a Fermi–Dirac distribution.
[src:mayer-s-relation/incompressible-flow] In fluid mechanics, or more generally continuum mechanics, **incompressible flow** is a flow in which the material density does not vary over time.
[src:mayer-s-relation/incompressible-flow] Equivalently, the divergence of an incompressible flow velocity is zero.
[src:mayer-s-relation/incompressible-flow] Under certain conditions, the flow of compressible fluids can be modelled as incompressible flow to a good approximation.
[src:mayer-s-relation/incompressible-flow] The fundamental requirement for incompressible flow is that the density, $\rho$ , is constant within a small element volume, *dV*, which moves at the flow velocity **u**.
[src:mayer-s-relation/incompressible-flow] Mathematically, this constraint implies that the material derivative (discussed below) of the density must vanish to ensure incompressible flow.
[src:mayer-s-relation/incompressible-flow] Before introducing this constraint, we must apply the conservation of mass to generate the necessary relations.
[src:mayer-s-relation/incompressible-flow] The conservation of mass requires that the time derivative of the mass inside a control volume be equal to the mass flux, **J**, across its boundaries.
[src:mayer-s-relation/incompressible-flow] The negative sign in the above expression ensures that outward flow results in a decrease in the mass with respect to time, using the convention that the surface area vector points outward.
[src:mayer-s-relation/incompressible-flow] The partial derivative of the density with respect to time need not vanish to ensure incompressible *flow*.
[src:mayer-s-relation/incompressible-flow] When we speak of the partial derivative of the density with respect to time, we refer to this rate of change within a control volume of *fixed position*.
[src:mayer-s-relation/incompressible-flow] By letting the partial time derivative of the density be non-zero, we are not restricting ourselves to incompressible *fluids*, because the density can change as observed from a fixed position as fluid flows through the control volume.
[src:mayer-s-relation/incompressible-flow] This approach maintains generality, and not requiring that the partial time derivative of the density vanish illustrates that incompressible fluids can still undergo compressible flow.
[src:mayer-s-relation/incompressible-flow] What interests us is the change in density of a control volume that moves along with the flow velocity, **u**.
[src:mayer-s-relation/incompressible-flow] The previous relation (where we have used the appropriate product rule) is known as the continuity equation.
[src:mayer-s-relation/incompressible-flow] So if we choose a control volume that is moving at the same rate as the fluid (i.e.
[src:mayer-s-relation/incompressible-flow] A change in the density over time would imply that the fluid had either compressed or expanded (or that the mass contained in our constant volume, *dV*, had changed), which we have prohibited.
[src:mayer-s-relation/incompressible-flow] And so beginning with the conservation of mass and the constraint that the density within a moving volume of fluid remains constant, it has been shown that an equivalent condition required for incompressible flow is that the divergence of the flow velocity vanishes.
[src:mayer-s-relation/incompressible-flow] In some fields, a measure of the incompressibility of a flow is the change in density as a result of the pressure variations.
[src:mayer-s-relation/incompressible-flow] If the compressibility is acceptably small, the flow is considered incompressible.
[src:mayer-s-relation/incompressible-flow] An incompressible flow is described by a solenoidal flow velocity field.
[src:mayer-s-relation/incompressible-flow] But a solenoidal field, besides having a zero divergence, also has the additional connotation of having non-zero curl (i.e., rotational component).
[src:mayer-s-relation/incompressible-flow] Otherwise, if an incompressible flow also has a curl of zero, so that it is also irrotational, then the flow velocity field is actually Laplacian.
[src:mayer-s-relation/incompressible-flow] i.e. the material derivative of the density is zero.
[src:mayer-s-relation/incompressible-flow] Thus if one follows a material element, its mass density remains constant.
[src:mayer-s-relation/incompressible-flow] Note that the material derivative consists of two terms.
[src:mayer-s-relation/incompressible-flow] The first term ${\tfrac {\partial \rho }{\partial t}}$ describes how the density of the material element changes with time.
[src:mayer-s-relation/incompressible-flow] This term is also known as the *unsteady term*.
[src:mayer-s-relation/incompressible-flow] The second term, $\mathbf {u} \cdot \nabla \rho$ describes the changes in the density as the material element moves from one point to another.
[src:mayer-s-relation/incompressible-flow] This is the *advection term* (convection term for scalar field).
[src:mayer-s-relation/incompressible-flow] For a flow to be accounted as bearing incompressibility, the accretion sum of these terms should vanish.
[src:mayer-s-relation/incompressible-flow] On the other hand, a **homogeneous, incompressible material** is one that has constant density throughout.
[src:mayer-s-relation/incompressible-flow] For such a material, $\rho ={\text{constant}}$ .
[src:mayer-s-relation/incompressible-flow] Thus homogeneous materials always undergo flow that is incompressible, but the converse is not true.
[src:mayer-s-relation/incompressible-flow] That is, compressible materials might not experience compression in the flow.
[src:mayer-s-relation/incompressible-flow] In fluid dynamics, a flow is considered incompressible if the divergence of the flow velocity is zero.
[src:mayer-s-relation/incompressible-flow] However, related formulations can sometimes be used, depending on the flow system being modelled.
[src:mayer-s-relation/incompressible-flow] Principally used in the field of atmospheric sciences, the anelastic constraint extends incompressible flow validity to stratified density and/or temperature as well as pressure.
[src:mayer-s-relation/incompressible-flow] This allows the thermodynamic variables to relax to an 'atmospheric' base state seen in the lower atmosphere when used in the field of meteorology, for example.
[src:mayer-s-relation/incompressible-flow] This condition can also be used for various astrophysical systems.
[src:mayer-s-relation/incompressible-flow] *Low Mach-number flow*, or *pseudo-incompressibility*: $\nabla \cdot \left(\alpha \mathbf {u} \right)=\beta$ .
[src:mayer-s-relation/incompressible-flow] The low Mach-number constraint can be derived from the compressible Euler equations using scale analysis of non-dimensional quantities.
[src:mayer-s-relation/incompressible-flow] The restraint, like the previous in this section, allows for the removal of acoustic waves, but also allows for *large* perturbations in density and/or temperature.
[src:mayer-s-relation/incompressible-flow] The assumption is that the flow remains within a Mach number limit (normally less than 0.3) for any solution using such a constraint to be valid.
[src:mayer-s-relation/incompressible-flow] Again, in accordance with all incompressible flows the pressure deviation must be small in comparison to the pressure base state.
[src:mayer-s-relation/incompressible-flow] These methods make differing assumptions about the flow, but all take into account the general form of the constraint $\nabla \cdot \left(\alpha \mathbf {u} \right)=\beta$ for general flow dependent functions $\alpha$ and $\beta$ .
[src:mayer-s-relation/incompressible-flow] The stringent nature of incompressible flow equations means that specific mathematical techniques have been devised to solve them.
[src:mayer-s-relation/mayer-s-relation] In the 19th century, German chemist and physicist Julius von Mayer derived a relation between the molar heat capacity at constant pressure and the molar heat capacity at constant volume for an ideal gas.
[src:mayer-s-relation/mayer-s-relation] **Mayer's relation** states that $C_{P,\mathrm {m} }-C_{V,\mathrm {m} }=R,$ where *C**P*,m is the molar heat capacity at constant pressure, *C**V*,m is the molar heat capacity at constant volume and *R* is the gas constant.
